&gt;Definition-Seriously Dead: A condition extremely more grave than Seriously Wounded, but considerably less painful.&lt;<br><br>
I know it's not Gerald's intention, but I found this joke to be offensive.  I have no idea what is funny about it.  I guess you are right, Dr. Spatz, my sense of humor sucks! How does one, whose job it was to be the platoon garbageman, picking up the torn and mutilated pieces and tossing them into bodybags, laugh about death and wounds.  And without remembering.<br><br>
Chet, the joke about Mr. Grenade, reminds me of a guy who had his face blown off, including his entire lower jaw, his eyes, and much of his neck.  I had to do a tracheostomy on him and clamp off one of his carotid arteries, as well as other bleeders.  We ended up carrying him with us for two days, depleting my sorry amount of supplies before he, mercilessly, died. I wish I saw even dark humor here. I couldn't even swear if he was conscious or not.  Anybody want to guess what was going through his head for those two days?<br><br>
I believe it was Tom and Arthur discussing boring and tedious times. There must have been those times for me, also, but I just can't remember it that way. We certainly were not engaged with Chuck 365 days a year.  Even during quiet periods, I can't recall them as &quot;tedious&quot;.<br><br>
I don't know.  I'm finding harder and harder to relate or understand things.  I am finding the need to yell and scream and rant and rave, and there is no one I can do this with. It's all getting too personal with me, and even with Wingman's assurance to cover my flank, it ain't enough.<br><br>
So, I appreciate meeting you all and for the interaction we had on this site.  Time for me to move on to more mediocre pastures.
